## Frontend: Wikipedia Map (controversial/wikipedia-map)

**Repo:** https://github.com/controversial/wikipedia-map
**License:** Open source — fork freely

-----

### What It Is

A web app that visualizes connections between topics as an interactive node graph. The user enters a topic, a node appears, they click to expand it, and new connected nodes branch out. This is essentially the same interaction model Fractal needs — it’s a near-perfect base to build on.

-----

### Tech Stack (What’s Inside)

**Graph Rendering:**

- `vis.js` (vis-network) — the core graph library that draws and animates all nodes and edges
- Hosted via CDN: `https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/vis/4.16.1/vis-network.min.js`

**UI Libraries:**

- `shepherd.js` — guided tour/onboarding for users
- `ionicons` — icon set for buttons (GitHub, help, shuffle, trash icons)
- `clipboard.js` — copy-to-clipboard functionality

**Frontend Files:**

```
index.html              ← main entry point, loads everything
css/
  style.css             ← main layout styles
  bar.css               ← top search bar styles
  buttongroup.css       ← bottom-right button group
  shepherd-custom.css   ← custom tour styles
  commafield.css        ← multi-topic input field
  welcome.css           ← welcome/info box
  modals.css            ← modal dialogs
  progress.css          ← loading progress bars
js/
  wikipedia_parse.js    ← fetches + parses Wikipedia API (REPLACE THIS for Fractal)
  helpers.js            ← utility functions
  main_functions.js     ← core graph logic (ADD NODES, EXPAND, COLOR)
  main.js               ← main app logic
  help.js               ← tutorial/tour logic
  bindings.js           ← event listeners (clicks, keypresses)
  commafield.js         ← multi-input tag field
  network_serialize.js  ← save/share graph state via URL
  loadsaved.js          ← load shared graph from URL
  modals.js             ← modal open/close logic
  progress.js           ← loading bar logic
```

-----

### How It Works (Original Flow)

```
User types topic → clicks Go
→ wikipedia_parse.js calls Wikipedia API
→ gets linked articles from first paragraph
→ main_functions.js adds them as nodes to vis.js graph
→ nodes colored by distance from center node
→ user clicks a node → expands further
```

-----

### How To Adapt It For Fractal

The key insight: **only one file needs to be replaced** to swap Wikipedia data for Fractal/LLM data.

**Replace `wikipedia_parse.js` with `fractal_api.js`**

Instead of calling the Wikipedia API, call your Groq/Ollama backend:

```javascript
// fractal_api.js — replaces wikipedia_parse.js

async function getSubPages(query) {
  const response = await fetch('http://localhost:8000/generate-map', {
    method: 'POST',
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
    body: JSON.stringify({ query: query })
  });
  const data = await response.json();

  // Return node names so main_functions.js can add them to the graph
  return data.nodes.map(node => node.name);
}
```

Everything else — the graph rendering, the click-to-expand, the animations, the UI — stays exactly the same.

